7.1.1 - W11SR12: Inadequate Management or Governance of AI Systems
ISM controls:
•	1884; 1885; 1886 (Relating to the secure development and deployment of AI and machine learning systems).
•	0013; 0015 (Relating to security governance and reporting).
•	0041; 1657 (Relating to the approval and control of software applications).
•	1644 (Relating to the use of approved cloud services, including AI-as-a-Service).
Current Risk
There is a risk that inadequate management, oversight, or governance of AI systems integrated into the Windows 11 environment (such as Microsoft Copilot or third-party AI tools) may lead to significant security events. This includes data manipulation, privacy breaches through data leakage, or the malicious control of AI-driven systems. Such failures could compromise the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of the system and its associated data, especially when handling sensitive government information.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
LIKELY	x	MODERATE	=	HIGH
Recommendations:
•	Establish an AI Governance Framework: Develop a formal policy governing the use of AI within the agency, ensuring all AI-driven features are assessed for privacy and security risks before being enabled on Windows 11 endpoints.
•	Implement Data Loss Prevention (DLP) for AI: Configure Microsoft Purview and other DLP controls to prevent sensitive or classified data from being ingested by AI models or exported through unvetted AI prompts.
•	Mandate AI Transparency and Explainability: Ensure all AI systems utilised have clear documentation regarding data usage, model training, and decision-making logic to facilitate effective security auditing.
- Treatment #1
•	Disable all unvetted AI features (such as Copilot for Windows) via Intune/GPO until a comprehensive IRAP assessment has been completed and the risk is formally accepted.
•	Conduct regular security reviews of AI "prompt logs" and output to identify potential misuse or attempts to bypass security boundaries (e.g., prompt injection).
•	Integrate AI security posture management into the existing vulnerability management lifecycle to address emerging AI-specific vulnerabilities.
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented.
By implementing strict governance and technical DLP controls, the agency can leverage AI capabilities while maintaining a defensible security posture. While the inherent complexity of AI systems keeps the consequence at "Moderate," the likelihood of a successful exploit or data breach is reduced to "Unlikely" through proactive monitoring and restricted deployment.
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
UNLIKELY	x	MODERATE	=	MEDIUM

